<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Two Sigma</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possibly relevant fact <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33194519.283415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqL=
mNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy9oZWRnZS1mdW5kLXR3by1zaWdtYS1pcy1oaXQtYnktdHJh=
ZGluZy1zY2FuZGFsLTUwMTkxM2NiP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB5e04bc22" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">here</a> is that $450 million is more than $170 million=
?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A researcher at Two Sigma Investments adjusted=
 the hedge fund=E2=80=99s investing models without authorization, the firm =
has told clients, leading to losses in some funds, big gains in others and =
fresh regulatory scrutiny.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The researcher, Jian Wu, a senior vice preside=
nt at New York-based Two Sigma, was trying to boost his compensation, Two S=
igma has told clients, without identifying Wu. He made changes over the pas=
t year that resulted in a total of $620 million in unexpected gains and los=
ses, according to people close to the matter and investor letters. Two Sigm=
a has placed Wu on administrative leave.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission is exam=
ining the matter. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wu=E2=80=99s changes led to gains of $450 mill=
ion in total for some Two Sigma funds=E2=80=94including those in which the =
firm=E2=80=99s own executives and employees invest, as well as those availa=
ble to clients. But they also led to a total of $170 million in losses for =
other funds compared with how they otherwise would have fared=E2=80=94losse=
s largely borne by clients. Two Sigma has made them whole.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People familiar with the situation said Wu was=
 trying to improve the firm=E2=80=99s performance, which would have benefit=
ed his career and potential pay.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean: Presumably everyone at Two Sigma is tr=
ying to improve the firm=E2=80=99s performance, because that would benefit =
their careers and potential pay? Like, what else are they coming to work fo=
r? If you find a tweak to the model that causes some of your funds to relia=
bly make an extra $450 million, while causing some other funds to reliably =
lose $170 million, then that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>good</em>. Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ideally, you go and=C2=A0make the twe=
ak to the model for the funds it would help, and leave the model for the ot=
her funds alone.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or if you can=E2=
=80=99t do that for some reason, then I guess=C2=A0you make the tweak to th=
e model for everyone, and have the benefited funds write a $171 million che=
ck to the harmed funds, leaving everyone better off.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I just think that if you tweak the model in su=
ch a way that clients make an extra $280 million, net, then that is broadly=
 speaking=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>work and you might reasonably expect your=
 bonus to go up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am kidding, I guess. It=E2=80=99s not that s=
imple. Presumably whatever the guy did did not=C2=A0<em>reliably=C2=A0</em>=
improve performance; presumably it improved performance over some period bu=
t at the cost of higher risk. That Wall Street Journal story adds:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two Sigma=E2=80=99s top executives=
 this summer became aware of Wu=E2=80=99s changes because they resulted in =
higher than expected correlations between some of the firm=E2=80=99s tradin=
g models. The trail pointed to Wu, who made the changes in two stages over =
the past year.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are in the business of maximizing risk-=
adjusted returns =E2=80=94=C2=A0or uncorrelated returns =E2=80=94 then some=
times higher returns are a leading indicator=C2=A0of trouble.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, there are a lot of stories in =
finance about rogue traders. Often the story is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some trader would like a bigger bonus=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">She does some trades that she is=
 not supposed to do, trades with higher risk (but also higher upside) than =
her firm wants.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The trades work, s=
he makes money, everyone is pleased.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Eventually the risks come true, she loses more money than she made, ever=
yone is mad and she gets in trouble.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are variations. One surprisingly popular=
 variation omits Step 3: Some=C2=A0rogue traders lose money pretty much fro=
m the beginning,=C2=A0so they=C2=A0keep doubling down. It is widely believe=
d that another popular variation omits Step 4, but you rarely hear about th=
ose: A rogue trader who consistently makes money=C2=A0stops being a =E2=80=
=9Crogue=E2=80=9D trader and becomes a star trader. (=E2=80=9CSorry I did s=
ome trades I wasn=E2=80=99t supposed to, but they all made money,=E2=80=9D =
she eventually tells her bosses, and they say =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s okay =
you lovable scamp, here=E2=80=99s a big bonus.=E2=80=9D) It is possible tha=
t in a modern age of strict risk controls, heavy regulation and careful per=
formance attribution, that approach no longer works the way it used to. But=
 you still don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>hear=C2=A0</em>about a ton of rogue trade=
rs who uniformly make money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway this story (a version of which was <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33194519.283415/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDYvdHdvLXNpZ21hL=
WFjY3VzZXMtZW1wbG95ZWUtb2YtbWlzY29uZHVjdC10aGF0LWNvc3QtY2xpZW50cy1tb25leT9j=
bXBpZD1CQkQxMDMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV=
3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB8659dae6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> previously reported by Bloomberg News</a>=
) isn=E2=80=99t that. It=E2=80=99s an alleged rogue-model-updater, or I gue=
ss rogue-model-calibrator:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a letter to clients, Two Sigma described th=
e activity as =E2=80=9Cintentional misconduct=E2=80=9D that violated the fi=
rm=E2=80=99s internal procedures. One person close to the situation dispute=
d the firm=E2=80=99s characterization, saying Wu adjusted how Two Sigma=E2=
=80=99s models were calibrated but didn=E2=80=99t alter the models themselv=
es. Calibration changes can be seen as more routine than a major change to =
the models.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Big firms such as Two Sigma usually closely mo=
nitor and are fully aware of all important changes to its trading models. =
=E2=80=9CIn well-run firms, all changes=E2=80=94calibrations or model chang=
es=E2=80=94are governed by procedures so that they must be disclosed and ap=
proved by the proper people,=E2=80=9D said Aaron Brown, a veteran quant who=
 wasn=E2=80=99t aware of Two Sigma=E2=80=99s situation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose this is the modern form of rogue tra=
ding: If you work at a systematic quantitative firm like Two Sigma, and you=
 go off and do some unauthorized trades, they are going to catch you pretty=
 quick because you=E2=80=99re not supposed to go off and do=C2=A0<em>any=C2=
=A0</em>trades. The computer tells you what trades to do; only trades bless=
ed by the computer can get done. If you want to be a rogue trader, you have=
 to be a systemic quantitative rogue trader; you have to put rogue signals =
into the model instead of trading on them yourself.=C2=A0If you want to do =
rogue trades, you have to rogue calibrate the model so that the computer ca=
n tell you to do the trades you want to do.</p>
