Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf66fb1ef" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  written in the past</a> abou=
t the oddly discontinuous math of celebrity wealth. There are two ways to m=
easure anyone=E2=80=99s wealth:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your wealth is based on your=C2=A0<em=
>past=C2=A0</em>earnings. Your wealth is the money that you have. You have =
worked for however many years at your job, you got paid some money each yea=
r, you spent some of it on expenses, and what=E2=80=99s left over is your w=
ealth. This is how most people measure their wealth. It=E2=80=99s how I mea=
sure my wealth, for instance. I look at my bank account and my investments =
and add them all up and subtract my debts and that=E2=80=99s my net worth.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your wealth is based on your=C2=A0=
<em>future=C2=A0</em>earnings. You have some expected stream of future inco=
me, and you can estimate the present value of that income (by doing a disco=
unted cash flow analysis, or just by multiplying it by some reasonable mult=
iple), and that is your wealth today. This is, classically, how=C2=A0<em>st=
artup founders=C2=A0</em>measure their wealth. If you start a company, and =
you give 75% of the stock to cofounders and investors and employees and kee=
p 25% for yourself, and the expected future earnings of the company are wor=
th $20 billion today, then your net worth is $5 billion. Even if the compan=
y has not made a penny yet,=C2=A0even if it loses money every year, even if=
 you take no salary. Your net worth comes from people=E2=80=99s expectation=
s of your future earnings.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most people use Method 1, and=C2=A0<em>it woul=
d be weird=C2=A0</em>for them to try to use Method 2. If you are 22 years o=
ld, just out of college, in $200,000 of debt, and=C2=A0starting your first =
job at an investment bank, you could say =E2=80=9Cwell I will probably go i=
nto private equity and make at least $2 million a year for most of the next=
 40 years, and at a reasonable discount rate, adjusting for the risk of it =
not working out, that contingent stream of income probably has a present va=
lue of about $10 million today; subtract my $200,000 of debt and add the $7=
00 in my bank account and you get a net worth of $9.8007 million, so I am a=
 millionaire.=E2=80=9D And you would not really be wrong! And in certain ci=
rcles you will get a sympathetic ear; some people will say =E2=80=9Cyes tha=
t is an appropriate way to account for your human capital.=E2=80=9D But mos=
t people will look at you funny.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/33194519.283415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjIvcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybS1nb3QtcmljaC1tYWtpbmc=
tcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybXMtcmljaD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMzAmdXRtX=
2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa614769a" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the=
re are ways</a> to switch between methods.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Let=E2=80=99s say you are a doctor in private practice, you make $500,=
000 per year, and you have $800,000 in the bank. You probably use Method 1,=
 meaning that your wealth is $800,000. But if you=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>1=
0% of your practice to a private equity firm, then (1) they will pay you 10=
% of the present value of your future earnings and (2) you=C2=A0<em>own=C2=
=A0</em>the other 90%, which now has a market value. If=C2=A0the private eq=
uity firm values your practice at 10 times earnings, then (1) they pay you =
$500,000 for 10% and (2) the remaining 90% is=C2=A0<em>worth=C2=A0</em>$4.5=
 million, making you a millionaire. Your net worth increased dramatically =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0from $800,000 to $5.8 million<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0just because someone put a price on your future ea=
rnings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a doctor in private practice and yo=
u=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>sell 10% of your practice to a private e=
quity firm, or even go out and get a bid, can you do this same math and say=
 =E2=80=9Cmy practice is worth $5 million so my net worth is $5.8 million=
=E2=80=9D? I mean,=C2=A0<em>I=E2=80=99m=C2=A0</em>not gonna stop you.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly if you are a working musician and yo=
u put your songs on Spotify and you earn $50, you have $50. If you earn $50=
,000, you have $50,000. But if you earn $50 million, the math changes: Now=
=C2=A0you have a catalogue of songs worth hundreds of millions of dollars, =
which is the present value of your expected future earnings. Some music inv=
estment firm would probably pay you hundreds of millions of dollars for tha=
t catalogue, if you want. Even if you don=E2=80=99t want, Bloomberg will do=
 the math for you and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/33194519.283415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9ncmFwaGljcy8yMDIzLXR=
heWxvci1zd2lmdC1uZXQtd29ydGgtYmlsbGlvbmFpcmUvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMzAyM19NT05FWV=
NUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzM=
TAzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd5f2ae4" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  declare you a billionaire</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taylor Swift=E2=80=99s Eras tour has generated=
 as much money as the economies of small countries. The movie version is ru=
ling the box office. Her new recording of a nine-year-old album, 1989, is e=
xpected to be one of the hottest-selling records of the year. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The success of the Eras tour=E2=80=94a Super B=
owl-sized event spanning numerous cities that has shattered records, sparke=
d ticket frenzies and even caused the equivalent of a small earthquake=E2=
=80=94has propelled the pop star=E2=80=99s net worth past $1 billion, accor=
ding to a Bloomberg News analysis. She=E2=80=99s one of the few entertainer=
s to reach that status based on music and performing alone, the result of w=
ork and talent, but also canny marketing and timing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of the accounting is realized cash earni=
ngs (from concerts, streaming, etc.), but $400 million of it is =E2=80=9Cth=
e estimated value of her music catalog,=E2=80=9D based on =E2=80=9Ca conser=
vative multiple of future royalties.=E2=80=9D Also based on comparisons to =
other artists who have sold their catalogues for nine-digit sums. Swift has=
=C2=A0<em>not </em>sold her catalogue, but that doesn=E2=80=99t change how =
the math works. The math is that she has a few hundred million dollars, so =
she=E2=80=99s a billionaire.</p>
